<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1933-09-06T13:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1933-09-06T13:00:00-05:00" n="653" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d653">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">341.1154L58/220: Telegram</note>
                            <head>
                                <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss>
                                    to the Ambassador in Great Britain</hi> (<persName type="to"><hi rend="italic">Bingham</hi></persName>)</head>
                            <opener>
                                <dateline rendition="#right">
                                    <placeName>
                                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1933-09-06T14:00:00-04:00">September 6, 1933—2 p.m.</date>
                                </dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>233. Referring to paragraph 5, enclosure 1, with your despatch No.
                                137 of August 4, 1933, regarding Lewis Gun claim, please obtain and
                                transmit copies of the laws and rules of Court which made possible
                                an appeal from the decision of Judge Darling to Court of Appeals and
                                thence to the House of Lords as alleged by Foreign Office.</p>
                            <closer>
                                <signed>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Hull</hi>
                                </signed>
                            </closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>